2 Multidimensional Spaces and MCMC

Multidimensional spaces look strange!

Cross Section of the Quintic Calabi-Yau Manifold

This image of quintic representation of Calabi-Yau manifold describes hidden dimensions of string theory.
Image was rendered by Andrew J. Hanson

In order to explore such spaces one needs MMC rather than independent Monte Carlo sampling.

Here is the result of three Markov chains running on the 3D Rosenbrock function using the Metropolis-Hastings algorithm.
The algorithm samples from regions where the posterior probability is high and the chains begin to mix in these regions. The approximate position of the maximum has been illuminated. Note that the red points are the ones that remain after the burn-in process. The earlier ones have been discarded.

The original uploader was Vzografos at English Wikipedia

3 Metropolis Algorithm

Create a function that makes decision for one step of Metropolis random walk based on the initial state and vector of probabilities.
Set vector of probabilities, for example:

probabilities<-c(.1,.3,.5,.05,.05)
sum(probabilities)
## [1] 1
init<-2

Repeat 100 000 steps and use the simulated trajectory to estimate probabilities of each state.
Compare these proportions with the defined probabilities.

(Do it yourself)

oneStep<-function(initSt,probabilities){
  numberStates<-length(probabilities)
  turn<-sample(c(-1,1),1)
  newStates<-c(initSt, initSt+turn)
  if (newStates[2]==numberStates+1) newStates[2]<-1
  if (newStates[2]==0) newStates[2]<-numberStates
  if (probabilities[newStates[2]]>probabilities[newStates[1]]) { 
    res<-newStates[2]
  } else {  
    p<-probabilities[newStates[2]]/probabilities[newStates[1]]
    res<-sample(newStates,1,prob = c(1-p,p))
  }  
  res
}  

trajectory<-rep(NA,100000)
for (i in 1:100000){
init<-oneStep(init,probabilities)
trajectory[i]<-init
} 
table(trajectory)
## trajectory
##     1     2     3     4     5 
## 10123 30245 49673  4947  5012
table(trajectory)/sum(table(trajectory))
## trajectory
##       1       2       3       4       5 
## 0.10123 0.30245 0.49673 0.04947 0.05012

4.2 Preparation of the model for JAGS

In order to prepare the model, first, clarify its structure for yourself.
It is useful to do it by creating a diagram, like in [K].
A tool for making such diagrams can be downloaded here.

Start with the simplest model that looks like this.

Interpretation of the diagram starts from the bottom.
Each arrow of the diagram corresponds to a line of description code for the model.

Line 1 of the model describes generation of the data according to the likelihood function: \(y_i \sim dbern(\theta)\).
Line 2 of the model describes generation of the parameter \(\theta\) from the prior distribution: \(\theta \sim dbeta(\alpha,\beta)\).
In this case parameters of the prior distribution should be defined. For example, \(\alpha = \beta = 1\).
The format of the model description for JAGS is a string:

modelString=" 
model {
  for (i in 1:Ntotal) {
    y[i]~dbern(theta)
  }
  theta~dbeta(1,1)
}
"

Note that variables names y and Ntotal match the names of the list of the data.
The syntax of the model description is model{description}.

The next step of preparation of the model description for JAGS is saving it to a temporary text file Tempmodel.

writeLines(modelString,con="Tempmodel.txt")

4.3 Initializing Markov chains

Performance of MCMC will greatly depend on initial values of random walks.
Some sources recommend dispersing starting values of different trajectories as far from each other as possible to guarantee good convergence and reliable estimation of time such convergence burn in period.
Other sources, including [K] recommend randomly concentrating them around MLE.
Probably, each approach may be good depending on properties of the model and complexity of the data.
For simple enough models when convergence is not expected to be an issue, pointing trajectories to the neighborhood of MLE may improve time of simulation.
In more complex cases it might be better to allow longer burn in period in exchange for good convergence check.

One way of initializing trajectories is to define a list of lists with their values. Alternative way is creating a function that returns an init value every time it is called. JAGS will call this function every time it starts a new chain:

MLE<-sum(y)/Ntotal
init1<-MLE
init2<-MLE*(1+.01)
init3<-MLE*(1-.01)
initsList<-function(){
  thetaInit<-sample(c(init1,init2,init3),1,replace=T)
  return(list(theta=thetaInit))
}
initsList()
## $theta
## [1] 0.303

4.4 Sending information to JAGS

Next step is getting all information to JAGS using jags.model() from library rjags.
This function transfers the data, the model specification and the initial values to JAGS and requests JAGS to select appropriate sampling method.

library(rjags)
jagsModel<-jags.model(file="TempModel.txt",data=dataList,n.chains=3,n.adapt=500)

In jags.model parameter n.chains specifies the number of chains to run (defaults to 1) and parameter n.adapt sets the number of steps JAGS can take to tune the sampling method (defaults to 1000).

The object returned by jags.model contains all information that we need to communicate to JAGS about the problem in the format suitable for JAGS.

update(jagsModel,n.iter=600)

The ânaiveâ standard error is the standard error of the mean, which captures simulation error of the mean rather than posterior uncertainty. \[naive~SE=\frac{posterior~SD}{\sqrt n}.\]

The time-series standard error adjusts the ânaiveâ standard error for autocorrelation.

coda::traceplot(codaSamples)

densplot(codaSamples)

plot(codaSamples)

Function traceplot() and densplot() show characteristics of the chains for each parameter; plot() shows the combination of both.

autocorr.plot(codaSamples,ask=F)

Autocorrelation function plot shows autocorrelations for different lags of the chains.

One measure based on autocorrelation function, called effective sample size (ESS) shows the size of the sample one would need to run to get a completely non-autocorrelated chain.
\[ESS=\frac{n}{(1+2\sum_k ACF(k))}.\]
The infinite sum usually stops when \(ACF(k)<0.05\)
In the best case scenario there is no autocorrelation in the chains and \(ESS\) is the same as the combined length of the simulated chains.
If there is a nonzero autocorrelation at lags up until \(k\) then the chain samples have to be thinned to leave \(k\) observations between consecutive values. This reduces \(ESS\).

effectiveSize(codaSamples)
## theta 
## 10002

The \(ESS\) number is consistent with the autocorrelation function.

Potential scale reduction factor or shrink factor introduced by Gelman is returned by gelman.diag().

gelman.diag(codaSamples)
## Potential scale reduction factors:
## 
##       Point est. Upper C.I.
## theta          1          1
gelman.plot(codaSamples)

Output of Gelman diagnostic contains the shrink factor and its upper 95% confidence level.

Gelman diagnostic measure called shrink factor is based on comparison of within chain variance and between chain variance.

Let \(\theta_{i,j}\) be the \(i^{th}\) sample of \(j^{th}\) chain, \(i=1,\ldots,n;j=1,\ldots,m\).
Then variance of chain \(j\) is \[s_j^2=\frac{1}{n-1}\sum_{i=1}^n(\theta_{i,j}-\bar{\theta}_j)^2.\] Average variance over \(m\) chains is \[\bar{s}^2=\frac{1}{m}\sum_{j=1}^m s_j^2.\]
Variable \(\bar{s}^2\) is called within chain variance.

Also define between chain variance as \[\bar{S}^2=\frac{n}{m-1}\sum_{j=1}^m (\bar{\theta}_j-\bar{\theta})^2,\] \[\bar{\theta}=\frac{1}{m}\sum_{j=1}^m \bar{\theta}_j.\]

Then estimated variance of stationary distribution is \[\hat{V}(\theta)=(1-\frac{1}{n})\bar{s}^2+\frac{1}{n}\bar{S}^2\]

Finally, Gelman measure of convergence called shrink factor is \[R=\sqrt{\frac{\hat{V}(\theta)}{\bar{s}^2}}.\]

If \(R\) is high (rule of thumb is \(R>1.1\)) then convergence is not sufficient and chains should be made longer.

5.2 Different group proportions, common prior

The model diagram looks like this.

5.2.1 Model preparation

Prepare the model string. It will be saved in the work directory.

  modelString = "
  model {
    for ( i in 1:Ntotal ) {
      y[i] ~ dbern( theta[s[i]] )
    }
    for ( sIdx in 1:Nsubj ) {      # Different thetas from same prior
      theta[sIdx] ~ dbeta( 2 , 2 ) # N.B.: 2,2 prior; change as appropriate.
    }
  }
  " # close quote for modelString
  writeLines( modelString , con="TEMPmodel.txt" )

5.2.2 Initialization and sending the model to JAGS

Initialize chains randomly around MLE.

  initsList = function() {
    thetaInit = rep(0,Nsubj)
    for ( sIdx in 1:Nsubj ) { # for each subject
      includeRows = ( s == sIdx ) # identify rows of this group
      yThisSubj = y[includeRows]  # extract data of this group
      resampledY = sample( yThisSubj , replace=TRUE ) # resample
      thetaInit[sIdx] = sum(resampledY)/length(resampledY) 
    }
    thetaInit = 0.001+0.998*thetaInit # keep away from 0,1
    return( list( theta=thetaInit ) )
  }

Check initiation:

initsList()
## $theta
## [1] 0.2861429 0.6247500

Send the model to JAGS.

parameters = c( "theta")     # The parameters to be monitored

burnInSteps = 500            # Number of steps to burn-in the chains
nChains = 3                  # nChains should be 2 or more for diagnostics 
numSavedSteps<-50000
nIter = ceiling(numSavedSteps / nChains )
# Create, initialize, and adapt the model:
jagsModel = jags.model( "TEMPmodel.txt" , data=dataList , inits=initsList , 
                          n.chains=nChains , n.adapt=adaptSteps )

5.3.3 Initialize function

Create function that randomly initializes chains near MLE.

(Do it yourself)

initsList = function() {
  resampledY = sample(y, replace=TRUE ) # resample
  thetaInit = sum(resampledY)/length(resampledY) 
  thetaInit = 0.001+0.998*thetaInit # keep away from 0,1
  return( list( theta=thetaInit ) )
}

Check initiation:

initsList()
## $theta
## [1] 0.5998

5.3.6 Find HDI of chains for treated and control groups

Use function HDIofMCMC() from [K] to find 95% HDI of the treated and control groups.

(HDIofChains.Contr<-lapply(codaSamples.Contr,function(z) Theta.Contr=HDIofMCMC(codaSamples.Contr[[1]][,1])))
## [[1]]
## [1] 0.06019314 0.62027963
## 
## [[2]]
## [1] 0.06019314 0.62027963
## 
## [[3]]
## [1] 0.06019314 0.62027963
(HDIofChains.Treat<-lapply(codaSamples.Treat,function(z)   Theta.Treat=HDIofMCMC(codaSamples.Treat[[1]][,1])))
## [[1]]
## [1] 0.4418011 0.9566669
## 
## [[2]]
## [1] 0.4418011 0.9566669
## 
## [[3]]
## [1] 0.4418011 0.9566669
plot(HDIofChains.Treat[[1]],c(.2,.2),type="l",col="orange",xlim=c(0,1),ylim=c(0,.8),
     xlab="HDI",ylab="Chain")
lines(HDIofChains.Treat[[2]],c(.4,.4),col="orange")
lines(HDIofChains.Treat[[3]],c(.6,.6),col="orange")
lines(HDIofChains.Contr[[1]],c(.3,.3),col="blue")
lines(HDIofChains.Contr[[2]],c(.5,.5),col="blue")
lines(HDIofChains.Contr[[3]],c(.7,.7),col="blue")

HDI at 95% cannot distinguish the two proportions.

5.4 Compare HDI bounds of hierarchical model and separate models

# Separate
plot(HDIofChains.Treat[[1]],c(.05,.05),type="l",col="orange",xlim=c(0,1),ylim=c(0,1),
     xlab="HDI",ylab="Chain")
lines(HDIofChains.Treat[[2]],c(.15,.15),col="orange")
lines(HDIofChains.Treat[[3]],c(.25,.25),col="orange")
lines(HDIofChains.Contr[[1]],c(.1,.1),col="blue")
lines(HDIofChains.Contr[[2]],c(.2,.2),col="blue")
lines(HDIofChains.Contr[[3]],c(.3,.3),col="blue")

# Hierarchical    
lines(HDIofChainsHierarchi[[1]][,1],c(.4,.4),col="purple")
lines(HDIofChainsHierarchi[[1]][,2],c(.45,.45),col="magenta")
lines(HDIofChainsHierarchi[[2]][,1],c(.5,.5),col="purple")
lines(HDIofChainsHierarchi[[2]][,2],c(.55,.55),col="magenta")
lines(HDIofChainsHierarchi[[3]][,1],c(.6,.6),col="purple")
lines(HDIofChainsHierarchi[[3]][,2],c(.65,.65),col="magenta")
legend("topleft",legend=c("Separate Left",
                          "Separate Right",
                          "Hierarchical Left",
                          "Hierarchical Right"),
       lty=1, col=c("blue","orange","purple","magenta"))

Hierarchical model shows some shrinkage and makes it more difficult separating the effects.
